"O'Reilly C.M., Alin S.R., Piisnier P.-D., Cohen A.S., McKee B.A.","Climate change decreases aquatic ecosystem productivity of Lake Tanganyika, Africa",2003,"Nature","424","6950",,"766","768",,,10.1038/nature01833,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0041967146&partnerID=40&md5=8bf5823f818850b61906c4ede1245d0a","Department of Geosciences, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ 85721, United States; Royal Museum for Central Africa, 3080 Tervuren, Belgium; Department of Biology, Namur University, B-5000 Namur, Belgium; Dept. of Earth/Environ. Sciences, Tulane University, New Orleans, LA 70118, United States; Environmental Science Program, Vassar College, Poughkeepsie, NY 12603, United States; Large Lakes Observatory, University of Minnesota, Duluth, MN 55812, United States","O'Reilly, C.M., Department of Geosciences, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ 85721, United States, Environmental Science Program, Vassar College, Poughkeepsie, NY 12603, United States; Alin, S.R., Department of Geosciences, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ 85721, United States, Large Lakes Observatory, University of Minnesota, Duluth, MN 55812, United States; Piisnier, P.-D., Royal Museum for Central Africa, 3080 Tervuren, Belgium, Department of Biology, Namur University, B-5000 Namur, Belgium; Cohen, A.S., Department of Geosciences, University of Arizona, Tucson, AZ 85721, United States; McKee, B.A., Dept. of Earth/Environ. Sciences, Tulane University, New Orleans, LA 70118, United States","Although the effects of climate warming on the chemical and physical properties of lakes have been documented, biotic and ecosystem-scale responses to climate change have been only estimated or predicted by manipulations and models. Here we present evidence that climate warming is diminishing productivity in Lake Tanganyika, East Africa. This lake has historically supported a highly productive pelagic fishery that currently provides 25-40% of the animal protein supply for the populations of the surrounding countries. In parallel with regional warming patterns since the beginning of the twentieth century, a rise in surface-water temperature has increased the stability of the water column. A regional decrease in wind velocity has contributed to reduced mixing, decreasing deep-water nutrient upwelling and entrainment into surface waters. Carbon isotope records in sediment cores suggest that primary productivity may have decreased by about 20%, implying a roughly 30% decrease in fish yields. Our study provides evidence that the impact of regional effects of global climate change on aquatic ecosystem functions and services can be larger than that of local anthropogenic activity or overfishing.",,"Ecosystems; Fisheries; Lakes; Proteins; Thermal effects; Nutrients; Global warming; aquatic ecosystem; climate change; lake dynamics; productivity; Africa; article; climate; ecosystem; global climate; lake ecosystem; priority journal; sediment; warming; water temperature; animal; classification; ecosystem; fish; food chain; greenhouse effect; metabolism; physiology; season; temperature; time; Africa; Animalia; carbon; fresh water; Africa, Eastern; Animals; Carbon; Ecosystem; Fishes; Food Chain; Fresh Water; Geologic Sediments; Greenhouse Effect; Seasons; Temperature; Time Factors",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; Carbon, 7440-44-0",,,,"McKnight, D., Brakke, D.F., Mulholland, P.J., Freshwater ecosystems and climate change in North America (1996) Limnol. Oceanogr., 41 (SPEC. ISSUE), pp. 815-1149; Molsa, H., Reynolds, J.E., Coenen, E.J., Lindqvist, O.V., Fisheries researh toward resource management on Lake Tanganyika (1999) Hydrobiologia, 407, pp. 1-24; Nixon, S.W., Physical energy inputs and the comparative ecology of lake and marine ecosystems (1988) Limnol. Oceanogr., 33, pp. 1005-1025; Coulter, G.W., (1991) Lake Tanganyika and its Life, , Oxford Univ. Press, New York; Plisnier, P.-D., Limnological annual cycle inferred from physical-chemical fluctuations at three stations of Lake Tan